        "Notice two things. First, all three ACF plots show no significant spikes at lags $h \\geq 1$ — the autocorrelations are statistically indistinguishable from zero, confirming that all three are white noise by our definition. Second, the ARCH(1) time plot clearly shows volatility clustering — stretches of large fluctuations and stretches of smaller ones. This structure is real and economically important, but it lives in the second moment (variance), not the first moment (mean), so it is invisible to the ACF. This illustrates precisely why the distinction between IID noise and weak white noise matters in practice.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "# Testing and Achieving Stationarity {#sec-testing}\n",
        "\n",
        "We have established that stationarity is essential for reliable time series analysis. The next question is practical: how do we determine whether a series is stationary, and if it is not, how do we transform it into one?\n",
        "\n",
        "This section develops the two main formal tests for stationarity — the Augmented Dickey-Fuller test and the KPSS test — and then discusses the transformations used to achieve stationarity in practice. We close with a full empirical application to US real GDP and CPI.\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Unit Root Problem\n",
        "\n",
        "The most important form of nonstationarity in economic time series is the **unit root** — a stochastic trend that causes the series to wander without bound. To understand what this means, start with the simplest case: the random walk.\n",
        "\n",
        "$$y_t = y_{t-1} + \\varepsilon_t, \\qquad \\varepsilon_t \\sim WN(0, \\sigma^2)$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Starting from $y_0$, we have $y_t = y_0 + \\sum_{s=1}^{t} \\varepsilon_s$. The variance grows without bound — $\\text{Var}(y_t) = t\\sigma^2$ — so the process is clearly not stationary. The hallmark of a random walk is that shocks are **permanent**: a positive shock today shifts $y_t$ up, and it never returns to its previous level. Economic examples include the level of nominal stock prices, nominal exchange rates, and price levels.\n",
        "\n",
        "Now consider a slightly more general process:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$y_t = \\phi y_{t-1} + \\varepsilon_t$$\n",
        "\n",
        "If $|\\phi| < 1$, this is a stationary process: shocks are transitory, decaying at rate $|\\phi|^h$ after $h$ periods. If $\\phi = 1$, we have a random walk. Subtracting $y_{t-1}$ from both sides and defining $\\delta = \\phi - 1$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\Delta y_t = \\delta y_{t-1} + \\varepsilon_t$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This simple rearrangement reveals the testing problem clearly. The unit root null is $H_0: \\delta = 0$ (equivalently $\\phi = 1$). The stationary alternative is $H_1: \\delta < 0$ (equivalently $\\phi < 1$). This is the regression we will estimate and test.\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test {#sec-adf}\n",
        "\n",
        "### From the Simple to the Full Test\n",
        "\n",
        "The **Dickey-Fuller test** estimates:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\Delta y_t = \\alpha + \\beta t + \\delta y_{t-1} + u_t$$\n",
        "\n",
        "and tests $H_0: \\delta = 0$ against $H_1: \\delta < 0$. This is a one-sided test. The intercept $\\alpha$ and trend term $\\beta t$ accommodate a non-zero mean and a linear trend under the alternative hypothesis. Three specifications exist depending on what we assume about the deterministic component:\n",
        "\n",
        "| Specification | Regression | Use when... |\n",
        "|---------------|-----------|-------------|\n",
        "| No constant, no trend | $\\Delta y_t = \\delta y_{t-1} + u_t$ | Series has no drift and is zero-mean |\n",
        "| Constant only | $\\Delta y_t = \\alpha + \\delta y_{t-1} + u_t$ | Series may have a non-zero mean |\n",
        "| Constant and trend | $\\Delta y_t = \\alpha + \\beta t + \\delta y_{t-1} + u_t$ | Series may have a linear trend under $H_1$ |\n",
        "\n",
        ": Dickey-Fuller specification choices {#tbl-df-specs}\n",
        "\n",
        "Always inspect the time plot before choosing a specification. Including a trend when the series has no trend, or omitting a constant when the series has a non-zero mean, leads to incorrect inference.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Non-Standard Critical Values\n",
        "\n",
        "The critical values for the Dickey-Fuller test are **not** the usual $t$-distribution values. Under $H_0$, $y_{t-1}$ is an integrated process, giving the OLS estimator $\\hat{\\delta}$ a non-standard asymptotic distribution — the **Dickey-Fuller distribution** — which is left-skewed and has more mass in the left tail than the standard normal. Using standard $t$ critical values would cause severe under-rejection of the unit root null. The correct critical values were tabulated by Dickey and Fuller (1979) and are built into all standard software.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Augmenting for Serial Correlation\n",
        "\n",
        "The basic Dickey-Fuller test assumes the error $u_t$ is white noise. In practice, most economic series exhibit serial correlation in their changes. The **Augmented Dickey-Fuller (ADF) test** adds lagged differences of $\\Delta y_t$ to absorb this serial correlation:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\Delta y_t = \\alpha + \\beta t + \\delta y_{t-1} + \\sum_{j=1}^{p} \\psi_j \\Delta y_{t-j} + u_t$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The null remains $H_0: \\delta = 0$, and the test statistic is the $t$-ratio on $\\hat{\\delta}$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\text{ADF statistic} = \\frac{\\hat{\\delta}}{\\text{se}(\\hat{\\delta})}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The augmentation lags do not change the asymptotic distribution under $H_0$ — we compare to the same Dickey-Fuller critical values.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Choosing the Lag Length\n",
        "\n",
        "Too few augmentation lags leave residual serial correlation, invalidating the test. Too many reduce power and waste degrees of freedom. Two standard approaches:\n",
        "\n",
        "**Information criteria.** Estimate the ADF regression for $p = 0, 1, \\ldots, p_{\\max}$ and select the lag length minimizing AIC or BIC:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\text{AIC}(p) = \\log\\hat{\\sigma}^2_p + \\frac{2(p+k)}{T} \\qquad \\text{BIC}(p) = \\log\\hat{\\sigma}^2_p + \\frac{\\log(T)(p+k)}{T}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where $\\hat{\\sigma}^2_p$ is the residual variance and $k$ counts the deterministic terms. The BIC penalizes complexity more heavily and tends to select smaller models.\n",
        "\n",
        "**General-to-specific (GETS).** Start with $p_{\\max} = \\lfloor 12(T/100)^{1/4} \\rfloor$ (the Schwert rule). Test whether the last lag $\\psi_p$ is significant. If not, drop it and test $\\psi_{p-1}$, continuing until a significant lag is found or $p = 0$.\n",
        "\n",
        "We use AIC-based selection throughout this textbook.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Interpreting ADF Results\n",
        "\n",
        "The output of an ADF test consists of three elements:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. The **test statistic**: a negative number. More negative means stronger evidence against the unit root null.\n",
        "2. The **p-value**: below 0.05 leads to rejection at the 5% level.\n",
        "3. **Critical values** at 1%, 5%, and 10%. If the test statistic is more negative than the critical value, we reject $H_0$ at that level.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-warning}\n",
        "## Two Common Mistakes\n",
        "\n",
        "**Mistake 1: Failing to reject $H_0$ is not evidence for a unit root.** The ADF test has low power against near-unit-root alternatives — processes with $\\phi$ close to but less than 1. A large p-value means the data are insufficient to reject the null, not that the series has a unit root.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Mistake 2: The specification matters.** Always match the deterministic terms to the visual behavior of the series before running the test.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## The KPSS Test {#sec-kpss}\n",
        "\n",
        "The ADF test has a unit root as its null hypothesis. This asymmetry matters: failing to reject the ADF null does not confirm stationarity — it merely reflects a failure to find evidence against the unit root. A complementary approach is to test with **stationarity as the null**, so that rejection provides evidence of a unit root. This is precisely what the **KPSS test** (Kwiatkowski, Phillips, Schmidt, and Shin, 1992) does.\n",
        "\n",
        "### The Regression Framework\n",
        "\n",
        "The KPSS test is based on the following decomposition of the observed series:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$y_t = \\xi t + r_t + \\varepsilon_t$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where $\\xi t$ is a deterministic trend (with $\\xi = 0$ for the level version of the test), $\\varepsilon_t$ is a stationary error, and $r_t$ is a random walk component:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$r_t = r_{t-1} + u_t, \\qquad u_t \\sim WN(0, \\sigma_u^2)$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The null hypothesis of stationarity corresponds to $\\sigma_u^2 = 0$: the random walk component is absent, and $y_t$ is stationary around a deterministic trend (or level). The alternative hypothesis is $\\sigma_u^2 > 0$: a unit root component is present.\n",
        "\n",
        "### The Test Statistic\n",
        "\n",
        "The KPSS statistic is constructed from the partial sums (cumulative residuals) of the series after removing its deterministic component. Let $\\hat{\\varepsilon}_t$ denote the OLS residuals from regressing $y_t$ on the deterministic terms (a constant, or a constant and trend). Define the partial sum process:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$S_t = \\sum_{s=1}^{t} \\hat{\\varepsilon}_s$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The KPSS statistic is:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\text{KPSS} = \\frac{1}{T^2} \\frac{\\sum_{t=1}^{T} S_t^2}{\\hat{\\lambda}^2}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where $\\hat{\\lambda}^2$ is a **long-run variance estimator** that accounts for serial correlation in $\\hat{\\varepsilon}_t$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\hat{\\lambda}^2 = \\hat{\\gamma}(0) + 2\\sum_{j=1}^{l} w(j, l)\\,\\hat{\\gamma}(j)$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Here $\\hat{\\gamma}(j)$ is the sample autocovariance at lag $j$, $l$ is a bandwidth parameter, and $w(j, l)$ is a kernel weight function (typically the Bartlett kernel: $w(j, l) = 1 - j/(l+1)$). The bandwidth $l$ must be chosen by the researcher — a common rule of thumb is $l = \\lfloor 4(T/100)^{1/4} \\rfloor$.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Critical Values and Interpretation\n",
        "\n",
        "The KPSS statistic has a non-standard asymptotic distribution under the null. Critical values differ depending on whether the test includes only a constant (level stationarity) or a constant and trend (trend stationarity):\n",
        "\n",
        "| Specification | 10% | 5% | 1% |\n",
        "|--------------|-----|-----|-----|\n",
        "| Level (constant only) | 0.347 | 0.463 | 0.739 |\n",
        "| Trend (constant + trend) | 0.119 | 0.146 | 0.216 |\n",
        "\n",
        ": KPSS critical values {#tbl-kpss-cv}\n",
        "\n",
        "**Crucially, the rejection rule is reversed relative to the ADF test.** Because the null is stationarity, a **large** test statistic leads to rejection. If the KPSS statistic exceeds the critical value, we reject the null of stationarity and conclude evidence of a unit root.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-warning}\n",
        "## The Bandwidth Choice Matters\n",
        "\n",
        "The long-run variance estimator $\\hat{\\lambda}^2$ is sensitive to the bandwidth $l$. A bandwidth that is too small underestimates the long-run variance, inflating the test statistic and over-rejecting the null. A bandwidth that is too large reduces power. In practice, most software applies automatic bandwidth selection; always check and report the bandwidth used.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "### Reading ADF and KPSS Jointly\n",
        "\n",
        "Running both tests and checking their agreement is the standard best practice. The four possible outcomes and their interpretations are:\n",
        "\n",
        "| ADF | KPSS | Conclusion |\n",
        "|-----|------|-----------|\n",
        "| Reject $H_0$ | Fail to reject $H_0$ | Evidence for stationarity |\n",
        "| Fail to reject $H_0$ | Reject $H_0$ | Evidence for unit root |\n",
        "| Reject $H_0$ | Reject $H_0$ | Contradictory — series may be near-integrated or have structural breaks |\n",
        "| Fail to reject $H_0$ | Fail to reject $H_0$ | Contradictory — insufficient sample information |\n",
        "\n",
        ": Joint interpretation of ADF and KPSS test results {#tbl-joint}\n",
        "\n",
        "When the tests agree, we can be reasonably confident in the conclusion. When they disagree — both reject, or neither rejects — the series is likely near-integrated, exhibits structural breaks, or the sample is too short to be informative. In such cases, additional tests and careful judgment are required.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Achieving Stationarity: Transformations {#sec-transformations}\n",
        "\n",
        "When a series is found to be nonstationary, the goal is to apply a transformation that removes the source of nonstationarity while preserving the economically meaningful variation. The two most common transformations are differencing and logarithms, which are often applied together.\n",
        "\n",
        "### First Differencing\n",
        "\n",
        "Taking first differences removes a stochastic trend. If $y_t$ is nonstationary but $\\Delta y_t = y_t - y_{t-1}$ is stationary, we say $y_t$ is **integrated of order one**, written $y_t \\sim I(1)$. If $y_t$ must be differenced $d$ times to achieve stationarity, it is $I(d)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "The economic interpretation of first differencing depends on the series. For a price level, $\\Delta y_t$ is the change in prices — inflation. For a nominal exchange rate, $\\Delta y_t$ is the change in the exchange rate. For a log series (see below), $\\Delta y_t$ is the approximate percentage change.\n",
        "\n",
        "Most economic level series are $I(1)$: GDP, price levels, exchange rates, asset prices. Their first differences are $I(0)$: growth rates, inflation rates, returns. This is one of the most important empirical regularities in macroeconometrics.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Logarithms\n",
        "\n",
        "Taking the natural log of a series with an exponential trend linearizes that trend, making it easier to remove by differencing. For a level series $Y_t$, we define $y_t = \\log Y_t$. Then:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\Delta y_t = \\log Y_t - \\log Y_{t-1} = \\log\\!\\left(\\frac{Y_t}{Y_{t-1}}\\right) \\approx \\frac{Y_t - Y_{t-1}}{Y_{t-1}}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "the last approximation holding for small changes. This means log-differencing gives us the **approximate percentage change** — a natural and interpretable unit for growth rates, inflation, and returns.\n",
        "\n",
        "The log transformation also stabilizes variance. Series that grow exponentially tend to have variance proportional to their level — a 1% change in a large GDP figure produces a much larger absolute change than a 1% change in a small one. Taking logs removes this level-dependence, making the series (closer to) homoskedastic.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Choosing the Right Transformation\n",
        "\n",
        "The choice of transformation should be guided by three considerations:\n",
        "\n",
        "**Economic interpretability.** Log differences give percentage changes, which are natural units for most macroeconomic and financial series. Level differences give absolute changes, which may be more natural for series measured in rates (interest rates, unemployment rates).\n",
        "\n",
        "**Visual inspection.** Plot the level series and the transformed series. If the log-level series has a roughly linear trend and the log-differenced series fluctuates around a stable mean, the transformation is working well.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Formal testing.** Apply ADF and KPSS to both the level and the transformed series. If the level series fails to reject the unit root (ADF) and rejects stationarity (KPSS), while the differenced series rejects the unit root and fails to reject stationarity, the transformation has successfully achieved stationarity.\n",
        "\n",
